\par\plain {\f2\fs20\b0\i0 Russell despised psychologism; he wanted a strict and clear relationship between analytical language (in logic and mathematics) and the physical world. Even as early as the\~Tractatus, Wittgenstein was focused on trying to deal with the paradoxes and outright holes in Russell\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s kind of analytical philosophy, though in the\~Tractatus\~he was merely looking for a means to limit philosophical language to what actually could be rigorously representative. By the time Wittgenstein got to the\~Investigations, he was fully committed to the idea that language was social and conventional, not objective and analytical, and while there was no way that Russell could refute that, there\u8217\'92s also no way that Russell could accept it without abandoning his own life-project.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0  }
